1
00:00:02,899 --> 00:00:07,503
Years ago, Judith Jarvis
Thompson put forward a hypothetical scenario.

2
00:00:07,503 --> 00:00:09,872
Suppose you wake up
in a hospital to discover

3
00:00:09,872 --> 00:00:12,842
that because you
have the same rare blood type,

4
00:00:12,842 --> 00:00:15,478
your circulatory
system has been connected to that

5
00:00:15,478 --> 00:00:19,349
of a famous violinist
with a serious kidney infection.

6
00:00:19,349 --> 00:00:23,386
The hospital claims you are now
morally compelled to stay connected until the

7
00:00:23,386 --> 00:00:27,690
violinist can function
independently, at least 9 months.

8
00:00:27,690 --> 00:00:31,594
Thompson asks whether you
would feel morally obliged to go along.

9
00:00:31,594 --> 00:00:35,531
Her point is that the right to a life
of one person does not override the right of

10
00:00:35,531 --> 00:00:38,935
another person to choose
what happens to his or her body.

11
00:00:38,935 --> 00:00:43,406
She argues that even if we grant
the humanity of the unborn baby, she has no

12
00:00:43,406 --> 00:00:47,944
ethical or moral right to the use
of her mother's body to sustain her life.

13
00:00:47,944 --> 00:00:50,079
It's actually not a very good argument.

14
00:00:50,079 --> 00:00:52,448
Francis Beckwith pointed out some ethical

15
00:00:52,448 --> 00:00:55,752
problems in his book
Politically Correct Death.

16
00:00:55,752 --> 00:00:58,388
Number one,
Thompson's analogy assumes all

17
00:00:58,388 --> 00:01:01,791
moral obligations
to offspring or voluntary.

18
00:01:01,791 --> 00:01:04,160
But both parents
have involuntary obligations

19
00:01:04,160 --> 00:01:07,864
because they had sex
knowing it could result in pregnancy.

20
00:01:07,864 --> 00:01:12,869
Number two, Thompson equates
volunteerism with family morality, which involves

21
00:01:12,869 --> 00:01:17,206
personal obligations to our
offspring, which we don't have to others.

22
00:01:17,206 --> 00:01:21,310
Number three, the preborn child has a
right to the mother's body because he or she

23
00:01:21,310 --> 00:01:25,314
is dependent on its
mother at this stage of development.

24
00:01:25,314 --> 00:01:27,350
And there's no reason to deny that right

25
00:01:27,350 --> 00:01:29,919
if the child is a
human, as Thompson allows.

26
00:01:29,919 --> 00:01:32,422
Number four,
abortion is not simply withholding

27
00:01:32,422 --> 00:01:36,059
treatment, but is
actually the killing of the baby.

28
00:01:36,059 --> 00:01:37,994
In the analogy, there's no guarantee the

29
00:01:37,994 --> 00:01:42,165
violinist will die, but
abortion is intended to kill.

30
00:01:42,165 --> 00:01:45,001
Thompson's point is
that a woman should have autonomy

31
00:01:45,001 --> 00:01:49,372
over her body and
everything in it, even another human being.

32
00:01:49,372 --> 00:01:52,508
By that logic, a woman
could continue drinking alcohol,

33
00:01:52,508 --> 00:01:55,878
knowing that the baby
could develop fetal alcohol syndrome.

34
00:01:55,878 --> 00:01:58,381
Who knows why someone
would do that, but then why would

35
00:01:58,381 --> 00:02:02,151
someone deliberately have
a baby chopped up and vacuumed?

36
00:02:02,151 --> 00:02:05,722
Terrible things can happen
when fallen human beings are in charge.

